                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851T.00/49a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Dakar (<persName type="to">Flexer</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-24T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 24, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>113. Department’s 107, October 13, 10 p.m. A telegram has been received from
                        Monrovia<note n="5" xml:id="d406fn5">No. 356, October 20, 11 a.m., not
                        printed.</note> to the effect that there is great unrest and some street
                    rioting at Dakar in protest over the compulsory evacuation <pb facs="0410"
                        n="404" xml:id="pg_404"/> of French women and children. It is for the
                    purpose of evaluating this and other alarming reports which are being received
                    about your district that the Department has requested you to keep it currently
                    informed on what is taking place and the state of public feeling.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
